      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f1531cab06c092e",
      "text": "* Slava Pestov: Creator of Factor. This was my first run in with a concatenative language. His demo was pretty compelling. I've tried to use the language / environment a few times since then, but haven't found a compelling use case to keep me in it enough to be productive. [https://factorcode.org/ homepage]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "52faf69e44bb40aa",
      "text": "* Kodu: A Microsoft Research project into creating a programming environment for kids. Unlike the majority of such efforts I have seen, this is a 3D environment. I downloaded it afterwards. When I later watched some tutorials, I found that it suffers the same malady as most visual languages. You eventually get to the point where you need some sort of global state and that needs to live somewhere. The only place it can live is attached to a physical object so you end up have to make up one to hold it (a rock in the case of the tutorial). That has always struck me an unintuitive , but I suspect it is inevitable when you try to map an abstract domain to a physical one."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "13e4e5822192dac4",
      "text": "* Alan Eliasen: Creator of Frink. This was by far the most entertaining talk of the entire camp. Frink is a language with a built in understanding of units. It allows you to ask crazy questions such as \"if all the people in China were to jump off a chair at once, how much force is generated and what magnitude of earthquake would that be equivalent to?\" I'm curious why more languages don't include things like this in their type system. [https://frinklang.org/ homepage]"
